"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Quincy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in France deriving their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Quintus</i>, meaning ‘fifth(-born)’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The earliest bearer of the name in England, that of Saer de <i>Quincy</i>, ancestor of the earls of Winchester, was from Cuinchy in Pas-de-Calais, but the name may have been reinforced by immigrants from Quincy-sous-Sénard in Seine-et-Oise or Quincy-Voisins in Seine-et-Marne. A family of the name <i>de Quincy</i> held the title Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Lucy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Lucie</i>, the vernacular form of   Lucia .  It is sometimes assumed that <i>Lucy</i> is a pet form of   Lucinda  , but there is no etymological justification for this assumption. It was in fairly widespread use in the Middle Ages, and increased greatly in popularity in the 18th century and again in the 1990s. In Ireland it serves as an Anglicized form of Irish Luíseach ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":41,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lucy de Quincy was born in 1218, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Richard Locke. She died in 1268, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1218–1268":"1218–1268","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1214–1303":"1214–1303","1241–1303":"1241–1303","1217":"1217","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1214":"1214","1268":"1268","1224":"1224","1299":"1299","1241":"1241","1218":"1218","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","Clifford Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Clifford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1218–1268":"1218–1268","1217–1299":"1217–1299","1214–1303":"1214–1303","1241–1303":"1241–1303","1217":"